<subSubSection pageId="38" pageNumber="39" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="38.[151,1436,325,818]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,397,422]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Belongs to the 
<taxonomicName box="[508,599,398,421]" class="Insecta" family="Nepticulidae" genus="Stigmella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nivea">
<emphasis box="[508,599,398,421]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">S. nivea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group. This relatively small species differs from other 
<taxonomicName box="[1331,1436,397,422]" class="Insecta" family="Nepticulidae" genus="Stigmella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1331,1436,397,422]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Stigmella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species, including the most similar 
<taxonomicName authority="Diskus &amp; Stonis" authorityName="Diskus &amp; Stonis" box="[552,826,433,458]" class="Insecta" family="Nepticulidae" genus="Stigmella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inca" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[552,629,434,457]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">S. inca</emphasis>
Diškus &amp; Stonis
</taxonomicName>
, 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[838,929,433,458]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[838,929,433,458]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, in the specific shape of gnathos with single very large caudal process and elaborated central plate. The irregularly scattered grey-white scales on grey forewing apex are also highly diagnostic.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
